The United States Agency for International Development (USAID) in partnership with Save the Children Tanzania has handed over medical oxygen supply equipment worth ($250,000) (over 500m/-) to four regional referral hospitals. The equipment will be used for COVID-19 case management of critical care patients in Sekou Toure Regional Referral Hospital in Mwanza, Dodoma Regional Referral Hospital (Dodoma), Bombo Regional Hospital (Tanga) and Mount Meru Regional Hospital (Arusha). A statement issued by Save the Children in Dar es Salaam on Friday said the equipment delivered to four regional health facilities were 656 oxygen cylinders, 20 handheld gas monitors, 184 pulse oximeters, 100 glucometers, 636 gauges and flowmeters with humidifiers, and 208 oxygen cylinder carts. Receiving the 500m/- support, the Chief Medical Officer Dr Wedson Sichalwe said the equipment will help to improve various health services in the country. On his side the Country Director of Save the Children, Bester Mulauzi said the reason behind the support was to support the government in ensuring that there is quality management of COVID-19 cases in the said health facilities. Meanwhile, USAID Health Director Ananthy Thambinayagam stated that the agency is committed to work collaboratively with the Tanzania’s Government and other stakeholders such as Save the Children to end the COVID-19 crisis. “The COVID-19 pandemic is among the most pressing challenges to the health, well-being, and economic security of all people. We must work together to address this pandemic with urgency,” USAID Health Director, Ananthy Thambinayagam said